  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities\n- Emerged prominently during Prohibition era in the United States\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First major U.S. legislation targeting money laundering\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established mandatory record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- Introduced international standards for combating money laundering\n- Encouraged global cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Key Milestones:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- 1990: First comprehensive international anti-money laundering recommendations\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act expanded legal frameworks after 9/11\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Frameworks:\n- Comprehensive regulations covering multiple financial sectors\n- Increased technological surveillance capabilities\n- Stricter reporting and compliance requirements\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legal landscape continues evolving with technological changes and emerging financial mechanisms.",
